1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,160
 Hello, and welcome to our lecture on semiconductors. In this lecture, we go from tubes to transistors

2
00:00:07,160 --> 00:00:12,920
 and semiconductors. So transistors were something that was discovered at Bell Labs in the quest

3
00:00:12,920 --> 00:00:17,320
 to build a better triode. They were trying to build a better tube. And there are three

4
00:00:17,320 --> 00:00:24,180
 basic kinds of materials with respect to electricity. There are conductors, like metal, this is

5
00:00:24,180 --> 00:00:29,900
 a wire, inside the wire is metal. Then there are insulators, like plastic, the outside

6
00:00:29,900 --> 00:00:33,780
 of this wire is plastic. That's why if there's electricity inside the wire, you can grab

7
00:00:33,780 --> 00:00:40,180
 it by the plastic, because the plastic insulates you. But for transistors, there's this thing

8
00:00:40,180 --> 00:00:45,320
 called a semiconductor, and it's certain crystalline materials, like silicon, that can be modified

9
00:00:45,320 --> 00:00:50,620
 by adding certain impurities, they call that doping. So these conduct electricity under

10
00:00:50,620 --> 00:00:57,480
 certain conditions, and hence they call them semiconductors, sometimes conductors. Here's

11
00:00:57,480 --> 00:01:04,880
 the basic picture of a Nobel Prize. You can create a transistor by taking some silicon

12
00:01:04,880 --> 00:01:09,320
 with a particular kind of doping, and a silicon with different, and touching them. And so

13
00:01:09,320 --> 00:01:14,480
 when voltages are applied to these crystals, subatomic stuff happens at the boundary that

14
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:20,120
 allows electricity to flow from one to the other. So it's actually at the boundaries,

15
00:01:20,120 --> 00:01:25,400
 right? So when these two kinds of material touch, that's what creates the transistor.

16
00:01:25,400 --> 00:01:31,320
 And in the early days, it was a kind of, it was a quest to take an input and a voltage

17
00:01:31,320 --> 00:01:38,640
 and make an amplified output. And so it turned out that transistors kind of did that, but

18
00:01:38,640 --> 00:01:44,720
 you can't, couldn't do what one tube did in a single transistor. And it turns out that

19
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:48,480
 the single transistor can be used to amplify, but it then flips the signal, and you've got

20
00:01:48,480 --> 00:01:52,600
 to unflip the signal back up. And if you look at it, it's not quite as high a quality as

21
00:01:52,600 --> 00:01:57,360
 a tube. So you add a couple more transistors, then the diode here and there, and a capacitor

22
00:01:57,360 --> 00:02:03,320
 to affect the, to make sure that any large DC voltages don't go through, et cetera, et

23
00:02:03,320 --> 00:02:07,840
 cetera, and some resistors. And you add all that stuff up, and you can make a pretty decent

24
00:02:07,840 --> 00:02:13,700
 amplifier at that point on transistors that you would have done originally with one tube.

25
00:02:13,700 --> 00:02:18,960
 And so one of the first things that I saw coming out were transistor radios. And so

26
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:23,760
 what was a radio? Well, it used to be something that sat in your house and you turned knobs

27
00:02:23,760 --> 00:02:28,880
 and whatever, and you went to the store and bought tubes when the tubes broke down. But

28
00:02:28,880 --> 00:02:33,400
 a portable radio, if you could use transistors, they were much smaller, and you could have

29
00:02:33,400 --> 00:02:39,920
 a portable battery powered transistor radio. Transistors are so exotic that in the early

30
00:02:39,920 --> 00:02:46,280
 marketing of some of these radios, they told you how many transistors was in the radio.

31
00:02:46,280 --> 00:02:53,520
 So here is a Sony eight transistor radio. And if you look closely, you can see it says

32
00:02:53,520 --> 00:03:04,720
 eight transistors. Now let's turn this on, see what we're going to get. This is the only

33
00:03:04,720 --> 00:03:10,400
 radio station that I could get inside this room, et cetera, but that is real AM live

34
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:18,360
 radio that is coming to this radio and being amplified by transistors. So let's take a

35
00:03:18,360 --> 00:03:24,600
 look at what's inside this. So now we have the back off of it. And you can see here,

36
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:29,760
 some transistors, some capacitors, and some resistors, just like what was on that circuit.

37
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:34,200
 So you can see these ones that have kind of the, they're round and they have a little

38
00:03:34,200 --> 00:03:40,640
 outline on top. Those are capacitors. So it has, you know, three, four, five, six capacitors.

39
00:03:40,640 --> 00:03:48,160
 They're used to filter out sort of high transient voltages. And then there's the, the transistors

40
00:03:48,160 --> 00:03:52,800
 are these little, there's the little things that don't have a circle on the top. They're

41
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:57,120
 little metal. You can take a look at the side of them to see how the transistors are built

42
00:03:57,120 --> 00:04:02,400
 right there as a transistor. And it, and then there's some resistors. You can kind of hard

43
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:07,920
 to see them. They're kind of tucked in between things. And so we have, I don't know, I can

44
00:04:07,920 --> 00:04:12,040
 count like one, two, well, there's eight transistors, because that's what it said it did. And so

45
00:04:12,040 --> 00:04:17,360
 this is what's inside of it. It uses explicit transistors and it was able to create a radio.

46
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:22,600
 The top, this top bit right here, that is the antenna for the radio. And so there you

47
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:31,120
 go. An eight transistor radio, probably from the 1960s, that still works today. So for

48
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:35,720
 a while it seemed like transistors were magic and everything that used to be done by tubes

49
00:04:35,720 --> 00:04:40,600
 was just slowly but surely replaced by transistors. The power was lower. Everything lasted longer.

50
00:04:40,600 --> 00:04:44,760
 You didn't have to worry about replacing the tubes. But then what happened is if you look

51
00:04:44,760 --> 00:04:50,360
 at the complexity of that circuit, you find that there's too many things in that circuit

52
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:57,020
 and purists who want perfect audio replication feel like so many transistors and resistors

53
00:04:57,020 --> 00:05:03,520
 and capacitors introduce noise. And so in recent years there has been sort of a throwback

54
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:08,680
 to tube-based amplifiers. And so you can buy these things, a brand new one can be over

55
00:05:08,680 --> 00:05:14,560
 50,000 and some of them are much higher than that. And so part of the reason is, is that

56
00:05:14,560 --> 00:05:21,160
 if you compare and contrast a single tube with a bunch of circuitry, you can see how

57
00:05:21,160 --> 00:05:26,360
 it might have some advantages. So I'll leave it up to the audiophiles to decide which is

58
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:31,940
 better. Also, high-end musicians tend to like amps that have tubes in them because they

59
00:05:31,940 --> 00:05:39,320
 feel that they give a more pure sound. Before we completely leave tubes and say goodbye

60
00:05:39,320 --> 00:05:44,000
 and move on to transistors for the rest of the class, I want to show you one last tube.

61
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:49,080
 It's called a Nixie tube. And it's going to appear later in the class when we do some

62
00:05:49,080 --> 00:05:54,920
 digital circuit design. This Nixie tube is a tube that has glowing numbers. And you can

63
00:05:54,920 --> 00:06:01,800
 see in the back, I have a working what we call Nixie tube clock. And I just want to

64
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:06,640
 show it to you to show how these numbers have sort of a dimensionality when they're moving

65
00:06:06,640 --> 00:06:12,840
 forwards and backwards. But what I like about the whole thing is I want to just show you

66
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:19,040
 the glow, right? That there's a certain glow and prettiness about tubes and those are electrons

67
00:06:19,040 --> 00:06:27,000
 that are making the shapes that glow. And I can kind of understand why it is that people

68
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:32,520
 who love audio love tubes, because not only can you listen to the audio, but you can also

69
00:06:32,520 --> 00:06:40,800
 watch the tubes as almost living analog creature doing your amplification. This is not a high-end

70
00:06:40,800 --> 00:06:46,560
 audio class, but this is kind of where we're going to take our leave of tubes and move

71
00:06:46,560 --> 00:06:54,080
 forward into a transistor only world. So the first thing, this is a graph that shows input

72
00:06:54,080 --> 00:06:58,200
 voltage versus output voltage. And so you could think of the input voltage as something

73
00:06:58,200 --> 00:07:03,160
 we're driving on the horizontal axis. And much like when we talked about making digital

74
00:07:03,160 --> 00:07:09,000
 tubes, the earliest kind of transistor was very an amplifier style transistor and it

75
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:16,400
 had a very much like a tube response and that it had a nice gradual slope, because you know,

76
00:07:16,400 --> 00:07:22,560
 you wanted the amplification of all the different frequencies and intensities of music to kind

77
00:07:22,560 --> 00:07:29,440
 of be consistent as you turn the volume up and down. But digital transistors, like digital

78
00:07:29,440 --> 00:07:34,800
 tubes, wanted to have a shorter transition. So again, you see this. Now I'll point out

79
00:07:34,800 --> 00:07:41,400
 that this is flipped from the tube one, because when a transistor is doing amplification,

80
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:46,040
 it kind of inverts it first. And that's why we had to put extra transistors in to make

81
00:07:46,040 --> 00:07:51,960
 a real amplifier. But the picture is kind of the same. You want for a digital transistor,

82
00:07:51,960 --> 00:07:58,360
 you want it to have a quick transition from high to low in terms of the output. So as

83
00:07:58,360 --> 00:08:02,640
 the input voltage is increased, you want it, you know, high, high, high, high and snap

84
00:08:02,640 --> 00:08:07,160
 low as fast as possible. The other thing you want is a regeneration thing. So you want

85
00:08:07,160 --> 00:08:14,800
 it to kind of come down about one third of the input voltage. And so that way that you

86
00:08:14,800 --> 00:08:20,000
 have if you put these in a sequence from one to the other, you're kind of regenerating

87
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:26,000
 the one and dealing with that sort of indeterminate state between zero and one. And so these are

88
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:31,440
 just designed slightly differently with different impurities and different silicon and different

89
00:08:31,440 --> 00:08:38,340
 manufacturing techniques. So over time, there was a couple of different kinds of transistors.

90
00:08:38,340 --> 00:08:45,440
 One was the transistor called NMOS, which conducts with the input gate is high and the

91
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:51,520
 PMOS that conducts with the input is low. And the most modern chips use a combination

92
00:08:51,520 --> 00:08:59,840
 of NMOS and PMOS transistors. As a matter of fact, there are four general areas of transistor

93
00:08:59,840 --> 00:09:05,920
 manufacturing and usage. So the earliest was the bipolar junction transistor, which is

94
00:09:05,920 --> 00:09:11,200
 more like a tube with that kind of linear response. They were fast and they knew how

95
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:17,240
 to make them in the early days, but they were power hungry and hard to integrate. And then

96
00:09:17,240 --> 00:09:22,040
 what we did is we made PMOS transistors, which were kind of large and clunky, but they were

97
00:09:22,040 --> 00:09:29,760
 easier to put together with early manufacturing imperfections. And they were slow. And then

98
00:09:29,760 --> 00:09:37,160
 we switched to NMOS faster and simpler, but both PMOS and NMOS by themselves wasted power.

99
00:09:37,160 --> 00:09:44,040
 And about 1983 and like the Intel 486, we switched to what's called CMOS, complementary

100
00:09:44,040 --> 00:09:49,600
 metal on silicon. And it was very low power and it was very scalable. And really from

101
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:56,280
 1983 till now, we can, we have pretty much to use CMOS and it really has to do with improving

102
00:09:56,280 --> 00:10:02,600
 manufacturing over time. So there's a whole bunch of different eras of manufacturing for

103
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:10,480
 transistors and we built computers throughout that whole era. And but today we do CMOS transistor

104
00:10:10,480 --> 00:10:13,080
 technology and talk about that in the next section.

